## Summary

The fix is a 4-line addition in `NoSemicolonsRule.kt` at line 98-103.

### Root Cause

When `ktlint --format` processes an enum class like:
```kotlin
enum class TestEnum() {
    A,
    B;
    companion object { ... }
}
```

The `TrailingCommaOnDeclarationSiteRule` (which runs late via `RunAsLateAsPossible`) correctly adds a trailing comma and moves the semicolon:
```kotlin
enum class TestEnum() {
    A,
    B,
    ;
    companion object { ... }
}
```

However, this AST manipulation moves the semicolon from being a child of the `ENUM_ENTRY` node to being a child of the `CLASS_BODY` node. 

During `format()`'s second pass (a lint-only pass on the corrected AST), the `NoSemicolonsRule` re-evaluates all semicolons. Its `isNoSemicolonRequiredAfter()` only recognized semicolons as enum separators when `node.treeParent.elementType == ENUM_ENTRY` (line 95). Since the semicolon's parent is now `CLASS_BODY`, the rule fell through to `return true` — incorrectly reporting the semicolon as "Unnecessary."

### Fix

Added a check in `NoSemicolonsRule.isNoSemicolonRequiredAfter()` for the case where a semicolon is a direct child of `CLASS_BODY` and its `prevCodeLeaf` belongs to an `ENUM_ENTRY`. In this case, the same `isLastCodeLeafBeforeClosingOfClassBody()` logic determines whether the semicolon is needed (it is, if member declarations follow).
